In Java, an array is a data structure that stores multiple values of the same type in a single variable, using an index.


An array is a fixed-size data structure that can store primitives and objects, while a List is a dynamic collection from the Java Collections Framework that stores objects and provides many built-in methods for manipulation.
Primitive arrays store actual values directly, while object arrays store references to objects. Primitive arrays have default numeric values, while object arrays are initialized with null.
# Declaration of array with primitive value  
Declaration	int[] arr;
Declaration + Size	int[] arr = new int[5];
Direct Initialization	int[] arr = {1,2,3};
Using new with values	int[] arr = new int[]{1,2,3};
2D Array	int[][] arr = new int[3][3];
Jagged Array	int[][] arr = new int[3][];

# Declaration of array with object value  
Declaration + Memory Allocation
String[] names = new String[3];


Feature 	Primitive Array	      Object Array
